 himself, a student of Socrates who had joined the Ten Thousand and, after most of the Greek generals had been murdered, rallied the despondent Greeks, won a position of leadership, and guided them wisely through myriad obstacles.In this new translation of the Anabasis, Wayne Ambler achieves a masterful combination of liveliness and a fidelity to the original uncommon in other versions. Accompanying Ambler's translation is a penetrating interpretive essay by Eric Buzzetti, one that shows Xenophon to be an author who wove a philosophic narrative into his dramatic tale.The translation and interpretive essay encourage renewed study of the Anabasis as a work of political philosophy. They also celebrate its high adventure and its hero's adroit decision-making under the most pressing circumstances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aAncient History & Classical Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aPhilosophy. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh  aAncient Greece.  aAncient Greek warfare.  aAncient drama.  aArtaxerxes.  aBabylon history.  aBabylon.  aCyrus the Younger.  aGreek historian and military leader.  aGreek literature.  aGreek scholar.  aGreek soldiers.  aXenophon history.  aXenophon.  aa band of Greek mercenaries.  aancient armies.  aancient battles.  aancient civilizations.  aancient greek military history.  aancient greek military strategy.  aancient greek political history.  aancient greek political philosophy.  aancient history.  aancient leadership.  aancient literary criticism.  aancient military history.  aancient military science.  aancient political philosophy.  aclassical literary criticism.  aclassics studies.  aepic story.  agreek military strategy.  agreek philosophy.  ahistory of political philosophy.  ahistory of political theory.  ains